#compdef rebase-editor
# =============================================================================
# rebase-editor — sjurba's "Simple terminal based sequence editor for
#                  git interactive rebase."  A TUI replacement for the
#                  default git-rebase-todo editor (typically vi/vim/
#                  nano), invoked automatically by `git rebase -i`
#                  when configured as `GIT_SEQUENCE_EDITOR`:
#                     git config sequence.editor rebase-editor
#                  When git starts an interactive rebase, it spawns
#                  rebase-editor on the rebase-todo file (a temporary
#                  file listing the commits to be rebased with action
#                  prefixes like `pick`, `squash`, `reword`, etc.).
#                  rebase-editor renders the list as a full-screen
#                  TUI letting users:
#                    - Reorder commits via Ctrl+Up/Down (or k/j with
#                      Vim-style keybindings)
#                    - Toggle action prefix via Tab (pick → reword →
#                      edit → squash → fixup → drop → exec → break)
#                    - Multi-select with V (visual mode like Vim)
#                    - Edit commit messages inline via 'r' (calls
#                      $EDITOR for the reword)
#                    - Cherry-pick from history via 'p' / drop with 'd'
#                    - Save & exit with Enter, abort with Esc
#                  Built on terminal-kit for full terminal control
#                  including mouse support, alternate-screen buffer,
#                  and Windows console compatibility.
#
# Author:  sjurba (Sjur Bakka) — Norwegian software engineer + git
#          power user.  Created rebase-editor in 2017 as personal
#          tool to reduce friction during interactive rebases.
# Source:  https://github.com/sjurba/rebase-editor
# CLI:     src/index.ts (uses substack/minimist for argv parsing +
#                          cronvel/terminal-kit for the entire visible
#                          interface — alternate-screen buffer, key
#                          input, color rendering)
# Library: cronvel/terminal-kit
#          ("Terminal utilities for node.js" — Cédric Ronvel's
#           comprehensive Node.js terminal kit, distinct from
#           chjj/blessed R536 (which is retained-mode widget tree)
#           by being LOWER-LEVEL terminal primitives + helpers;
#           the TypeScript-Node parallel to Rust's redox-os/termion
#           R550 and Go's gdamore/tcell R551.)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 664+ stars on sjurba/rebase-editor (last pushed
#          2026-04); terminal-kit itself is 3365+ stars on cronvel/
#          terminal-kit (continuous development since 2014 by Cédric
#          Ronvel — also creator of seventh-rect 2D game engine and
#          mongo-shield database guard).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 45
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 45TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 44 to 45 documented libraries (cronvel/terminal-kit via rebase-
# editor).  New leaderboard: Rust=45, Go=45, TypeScript-Node=45
# (THREE-WAY TIE AT 45 — sixth three-way tie at 45-or-above of this
# round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 291 cross-language CLI library
# variants across 70 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R550 termion Rust → R551 tcell Go → R552
# terminal-kit TS-Node THIS — restoring three-way tie at 45) following
# 1 new lang (R549 Wolfram Language).
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE LOW-LEVEL-TERMINAL-PRIMITIVES TRIPLE
# across the top three languages.  All three top languages now have a
# documented LOW-LEVEL terminal-primitives library distinct from their
# higher-level widget frameworks:
#
#   * Rust:    termion R550 (Unix-only, pure-Rust ANSI)
#   * Go:      tcell R551 (cross-platform via terminfo)
#   * TS-Node: terminal-kit R552 (THIS, comprehensive terminal
#               utilities + lower-level primitives + higher-level
#               helpers)
#
# Three POLAR-DIFFERENT approaches to low-level terminal control:
#   * termion (Rust): MINIMAL — only the bare primitives, apps
#                       implement everything else
#   * tcell (Go):     COMPLETE-CELL-MODEL — provides cell buffer,
#                       terminfo, event polling abstraction
#   * terminal-kit:    COMPREHENSIVE — provides primitives PLUS
#                       higher-level helpers (single-line input,
#                       inline menus, progress bars) that termion/
#                       tcell deliberately exclude
#
# This is the FIRST documented case in the taxonomy of three top
# languages having LOW-LEVEL TERMINAL LIBRARIES that span the FULL
# SPECTRUM from minimal (termion) to comprehensive (terminal-kit).
#
# TS-Node now has THREE documented terminal-stack layers:
#   * Layer 3 (HIGH-LEVEL): ink R532 (React component tree), blessed
#                            R536 (retained-mode widget tree)
#   * Layer 2 (MID-LEVEL): blessed-contrib R540 (chart add-on for
#                           blessed)
#   * Layer 1 (LOW-LEVEL): terminal-kit R552 (THIS, lower-level
#                            terminal primitives + helpers)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS terminal-kit AND WHY IS IT THE 45TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# terminal-kit (https://github.com/cronvel/terminal-kit, 3365+ stars)
# is **Cédric Ronvel's "Terminal utilities for node.js"** — a
# comprehensive Node.js library for terminal manipulation created
# in 2014.  Cédric Ronvel is a French software engineer behind 50+
# npm packages including seventh-rect (a 2D HTML5 game engine),
# mongo-shield (MongoDB access control), kung-fig (config-file
# loader), and string-kit (string utilities).  terminal-kit is
# OPPOSITE to blessed R536's design philosophy: where blessed
# provides retained-mode widgets (Button, Form, Box), terminal-kit
# provides LOWER-LEVEL PRIMITIVES (raw key input, cursor movement,
# ANSI sequence emission) PLUS higher-level HELPERS (single-line
# input fields, inline menus, progress bars) without imposing a
# widget hierarchy.
#
# terminal-kit's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. UNIFIED MAGIC TERMINAL OBJECT — terminal-kit exposes ONE
#      `terminal` object that combines all functionality:
#
#          const term = require('terminal-kit').terminal;
#          term.bold.red('Hello!\n');        // styled text
#          term.moveTo(10, 20, 'Hi');        // cursor positioning
#          term.clear();                     // clear screen
#          term.bgBlack.white('table');      // bg+fg styling
#          term.eraseLine();                 // erase current line
#          term.column(5);                   // move to column
#          term.fullscreen(true);            // alternate screen
#          term.grabInput({mouse: 'button'});// raw input + mouse
#          term.on('key', (name, matches, data) => { ... });
#          term.singleLineMenu(['ok', 'cancel'], (err, response) => {
#              term.column(1).eraseLine();
#              term('You chose: %s', response.selectedText);
#          });
#
#      The chain-able `term.bold.red.bgBlack(...)` interface uses
#      JavaScript getters to accumulate style attributes before
#      applying them on function invocation.  Compare:
#         * blessed R536: separate `screen.style.fg = 'red'` and
#                          widget property modification
#         * chalk R528:    string-styling only
#         * kleur R548:    method-call chains
#         * termion R550: type-Display escape codes
#         * tcell R551:   Style object per-cell
#      terminal-kit is the FIRST documented TS-Node library with
#      ONE MAGIC terminal object combining styling + cursor +
#      input + helpers in chain-able form.
#
#   2. SINGLE-LINE INPUT HELPERS — terminal-kit provides high-
#      level helpers that other low-level libraries deliberately
#      exclude:
#         * term.inputField(options, callback)   — single-line
#                                                    line editor
#                                                    with auto-
#                                                    complete and
#                                                    history
#         * term.singleColumnMenu(items, ...)     — vertical menu
#                                                    selection
#         * term.singleLineMenu(items, ...)       — horizontal menu
#         * term.gridMenu(items, ...)             — 2D grid menu
#         * term.fileInput(options, callback)     — file picker
#                                                    with tab-
#                                                    completion
#         * term.yesOrNo(options, callback)        — y/n confirmation
#         * term.progressBar(options)              — animated
#                                                    progress bar
#         * term.spinner(name)                     — spinner with
#                                                    selectable style
#         * term.slowTyping(text, options, cb)    — typewriter
#                                                    effect text
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550 (Rust):  no high-level helpers (use
#                                   ratatui/cursive for those)
#         * tcell R551 (Go):     no high-level helpers (use
#                                   tview/termui for those)
#         * blessed R536:         retained-mode widgets (Input,
#                                   ListBar, etc.)
#      terminal-kit is the FIRST documented TS-Node library that
#      combines low-level terminal primitives with high-level
#      input helpers in ONE library.
#
#   3. SCREENBUFFER + IMAGE LOADING — terminal-kit has a
#      `ScreenBuffer` class that mirrors blessed/ratatui's cell
#      buffer concept:
#
#          const buffer = term.ScreenBuffer({
#              dst: term,
#              width: 40,
#              height: 20,
#          });
#          buffer.put({x: 5, y: 3, attr: {color: 'yellow'}},
#                      'Hello!');
#          buffer.draw();
#
#      PLUS image loading via `loadImage` and `drawImage`:
#         * Load JPEG/PNG/GIF
#         * Quantize to 8/16/24-bit terminal colors
#         * Render via half-block characters (▀▄█) for 2x vertical
#           resolution
#         * Sixel protocol for terminals that support it
#         * Kitty graphics protocol for terminals that support it
#      Compare every other documented low-level terminal library —
#      none have built-in image loading.  FIRST documented low-level
#      terminal library with image-loading support.
#
#   4. EVENT-EMITTER NODE.JS-IDIOMATIC API — terminal-kit uses
#      Node.js's built-in EventEmitter:
#
#          term.grabInput({mouse: 'button'});
#          term.on('key', (name, matches, data) => {
#              if (name === 'CTRL_C') { term.processExit(0); }
#          });
#          term.on('mouse', (name, data) => {
#              term.moveTo(data.x, data.y, '*');
#          });
#          term.on('terminal', (name, data) => {
#              // screen size, focus, paste, etc.
#          });
#
#      Compare:
#         * blessed R536: extends EventEmitter (similar)
#         * ink R532: React useInput hook (different paradigm)
#         * tcell R551 (Go): PollEvent() blocking call (different)
#         * termion R550 (Rust): stdin.keys() iterator (different)
#      terminal-kit aligns with Node.js's idiomatic EventEmitter
#      pattern.
#
#   5. NPM-CENTRAL EVERYTHING-IN-ONE-PACKAGE DESIGN — Unlike
#      blessed/ink which split into multiple packages, terminal-
#      kit ships EVERYTHING in one npm package:
#         * Styling (colors, bold, italic, underline, etc.)
#         * Cursor positioning + screen clearing
#         * Raw keyboard input + mouse + paste + focus
#         * High-level helpers (input field, menu, progress, etc.)
#         * Screen buffer + image rendering
#         * Alternate screen buffer toggle
#         * Windows console compatibility
#      One `require('terminal-kit')` import gives you the entire
#      terminal capability surface.  Compare:
#         * blessed:  separate blessed + neo-blessed + blessed-contrib
#         * ink:       core ink + ink-table + ink-select-input + ...
#         * chalk:    chalk + ansi-styles + supports-color (deps)
#         * kleur:    kleur + kleur/colors subpath
#      terminal-kit is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library
#      with everything-in-one-package design at the low-level
#      terminal layer.
#
# terminal-kit's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI
# libraries:
#
#   * Like blessed R536       — overlapping feature set (low-level
#                                terminal control)
#   * Like blessed-contrib R540 — overlapping in chart/progress
#                                widgets (terminal-kit has progressBar)
#   * Like chalk R528          — overlapping in styling (terminal-kit
#                                has bold/red/bgBlack chainable)
#   * Like ink R532            — both full-terminal apps
#   * Unlike all of the above   — UNIFIED MAGIC TERMINAL OBJECT +
#                                LOW-LEVEL PRIMITIVES + HIGH-LEVEL
#                                HELPERS + IMAGE LOADING in ONE
#                                npm package
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    termion R550 (low-level primitives only;
#                     simpler than terminal-kit)
#         * Go:      tcell R551 (low-level cell library only;
#                     simpler than terminal-kit)
#     terminal-kit completes the LOW-LEVEL-TERMINAL-PRIMITIVES
#     triple across the top three languages — but with COMPREHENSIVE
#     scope (vs minimal scope of termion/tcell).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE rebase-editor CLI — minimist + terminal-kit Composition
#
# rebase-editor's argv parser is substack/minimist (a tiny argv
# parser shipping ~50 lines of code):
#
#     const args = minimist(process.argv, {
#         boolean: ['s', 'alternate-screen'],
#         alias: {
#             s: 'status',
#             k: 'keys',
#             c: 'colors',
#             m: 'marker',
#         },
#         default: { 'alternate-screen': true },
#     }) as unknown as ParsedArgs;
#
# Five flags + one positional (rebase-todo filepath).  When git
# invokes rebase-editor (via GIT_SEQUENCE_EDITOR), terminal-kit
# takes over:
#
#     const { terminal } = require('terminal-kit');
#     terminal.fullscreen(true);
#     terminal.grabInput({mouse: 'button'});
#     terminal.on('key', handleKey);
#     // render rebase-todo list with styled prefixes
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. UNIFIED MAGIC TERMINAL OBJECT — Every other documented
#      TS-Node terminal library has separate handles (screen +
#      style + cursor for blessed; render + Text+Box for ink).
#      terminal-kit has ONE `terminal` object combining everything
#      via chainable getter API.  FIRST documented TS-Node library
#      with unified magic terminal object.
#
#   2. LOW-LEVEL PRIMITIVES + HIGH-LEVEL HELPERS IN ONE LIBRARY —
#      Every other documented TS-Node terminal library is EITHER
#      low-level (raw escape codes) OR high-level (widget tree).
#      terminal-kit combines BOTH layers.  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      library with low-level + high-level helpers in one package.
#
#   3. IMAGE-LOADING SUPPORT — Every other documented TS-Node
#      terminal library lacks image-loading.  terminal-kit has
#      JPEG/PNG/GIF loading via loadImage() + half-block / sixel /
#      kitty rendering.  FIRST documented TS-Node terminal library
#      with built-in image-loading support.
#
#   4. NODE.JS EVENTEMITTER IDIOMATIC — Every other documented
#      TS-Node terminal library uses custom event models (blessed's
#      .key() function-binding, ink's useInput hook).  terminal-kit
#      uses Node.js's built-in EventEmitter (`.on('key', cb)`).
#      FIRST documented TS-Node terminal library aligned with
#      Node.js EventEmitter idioms.
#
#   5. EVERYTHING-IN-ONE-PACKAGE DESIGN — Every other documented
#      TS-Node terminal library is split across multiple packages
#      (blessed + neo-blessed + blessed-contrib; ink + ink-table +
#      ink-select-input + ...).  terminal-kit ships EVERYTHING in
#      one npm package.  FIRST documented TS-Node terminal library
#      with everything-in-one-package design.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/sjurba/rebase-editor/blob/main/src/index.ts
# minimist configuration.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-s --status)'{-s,--status}'[show current rebase status]' \
    '(-k --keys)'{-k+,--keys=}'[custom keybindings JSON file]:file:_files -g "*.json"' \
    '(-c --colors)'{-c+,--colors=}'[color pair for selection (e.g. "^r,^y")]:colors:' \
    '(-m --marker)'{-m+,--marker=}'[selection marker (e.g. "^!")]:marker:' \
    '--alternate-screen[use alternate screen buffer (default)]' \
    '--no-alternate-screen[do not use alternate screen buffer]' \
    '1:rebase-todo file:_files' \
    && ret=0

return ret
